## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow + Thread.ResetAbort

Your code has three APIs that don't work in .NET 6+:
- `thread.Abort()` → throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`
- `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → never thrown
- `Thread.ResetAbort()` → throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException if the
            // token fires before the task completes (.NET 6+ API).
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ae.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key changes

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) |
|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(work, token)` |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` — auto-cancels |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed — not needed with cooperative cancellation |

### Critical pitfall: cancellation is cooperative now

`Thread.Abort` forcibly injected an exception mid-execution. `CancellationToken` does **not** — the work function must voluntarily check for cancellation. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop or a blocking synchronous call that never checks the token, **it will keep running after the timeout**.

To make `work` actually stoppable, pass the token through:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller must cooperate:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Other pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Leaked `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using` — it holds timer resources |
| **`Thread.Sleep` ignores tokens** | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` inside work |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures only *your* timeout triggers the catch — other cancellations propagate |
| **Fire-and-forget task** | After timeout, the `Task.Run` work may still be running in the background consuming resources until it hits a checkpoint |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If `work` calls a library you can't modify, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only true equivalent of the old `Thread.Abort` |
